a fraction ~0.7 of\nthe CH4 ice in the larger lobe to melt and for a fraction ~0.4 of the CO2 ice\nto sublime. For the smaller lobe, these fractions are less. Liquid CH4 quickly\nmigrates upwards to the surface and refreezes to form a thick outer shell of\nCH4 ice. The sublimation of CO2 takes place after the melting of CH4. The\npossibility now exists for rising CO2 vapour to become trapped beneath the CH4\nshell. This may lead to explosive eruptions of the outer shell and destruction\nof the primordial surface of Ultima and loss of the CO2. If 60% of CO2 is lost,\nthe lobe radii each shrinks by ~5%. Even so, the intensity of 26Al radiogenic\nheating may not be sufficient to render the surface of Ultima Thule globally\nsmooth, unless the lobe sizes are of order ~15 km.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 9 Jan 2019 17:57:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 18 Jan 2019 12:37:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-01-21"}
